
George W. Bush's political positions have been expressed in public statements, and through his actions as President of the United States.
Economic policy
Fiscal policy and taxation
Energy policy
George Bush supports nukuler power and opposes green energy. He unsigned the Kyoto Protocol and supports drilling in ANWR.
Free-market capitalism
Bush is a supporter of free trade, calling on nations to embrace free trade even as turmoil raced through the world's markets in the 2008 financial crisis. 1
Trade
Subprime mortgage crisis relief
Health care
In 2004, Bush planned a health care program that would supposedly cover as many as 10 million people who lack health insurance at a cost of $102 billion over the next decade, though the Washington Post is skeptical. 2
Campaign finance
Workers' issues and labor unions
Social Security Tax Cap
Foreign policy
Iraq War
On March 19, 2003, Bush ordered an invasion of Iraq, launching the Iraq War. That night, he addressed the nation, stating that he decided to invade Iraq &quot;to disarm Iraq, to free its people and to defend the world from grave danger&quot;This was said to be a big mistake.
